value.value: A unit of measure expressed in microliter(s) per dose.
A unit of fraction expressed as the ratio of the number of micromoles of substance per unit of time equal to one hour, to the amount of a different substance, in millimoles.
A concentration unit equal to one micromole of solute in one liter of solution per unit of time equal to one hour.
An arbitrary unit of substance content expressed in microunit(s) per deciliter.

Clusters of neurons comprising the globus pallidus, putamen, caudate, nucleus accumbens, substantia nigra and subthalamic nucleus. They are involved with high level aspects of inhibitory motor activity in coordination with the excitation commands issued from the cerebellum.
An arbitrary unit of substance content expressed in microunit(s) per liter.
A unit for cloning vector amounts expressed as the number of vector genomes per dose.
A unit for cloning vector amounts expressed as the number of vector genomes per milliliter.
A unit for virus amount expressed as the number of viral particles per dose.
A unit for virus amount expressed as the number of viral particles per milliliter.
A circumferential measurement of the largest part of the upper arm.

label.value: Gravid Uterus Adjusted Maternal Body Weight Gain

value.value: The amount of maternal body weight gained over a period of time where the weight at the end of the interval is adjusted for the gravid uterus weight. This is derived by subtracting the maternal body weight adjusted for the gravid uterus from the total maternal body weight.

label.value: Gravid Uterus Adjusted Maternal Body Weight

value.value: The maternal body weight adjusted for the weight of the gravid uterus. This is derived by subtracting the gravid uterus weight from the total maternal body weight.
A measurement of the length of the span between the protuberances of the parietal bones of the skull.
An estimate or direct measurement of the heaviness of a fetus.
The striped grey and white matter that comprises the caudate and the lentiform nuclei, and is located anterior and lateral to the thalamus in each hemisphere of the brain.
The amount of three dimensional space occupied by a fluid.
A measurement of the skull diameter, measured from the external occipital protuberance to the most prominent point of the frontal bone in the midline.
A measurement of the number of skeletal elements with ossification centers present.
An estimate or direct measurement of the heaviness of a fetal organ.
The determination of the sex of the fetus.
A change resulting in a consistency that is different from the original.
An aberrant or malpositioned long, narrow slit or groove that divides a tissue into distinct areas.
A flexure that is deviating from the norm or outwith the bounds of what is considered normal.
The formation of a lobe of tissue that is aberrant in comparison to normal anatomy.
An origin that is deviating from the norm or outwith the bounds of what is considered normal.

A sub-cortical, paired nuclei that, though migrated to the telencephalon, is a critical part of the basal ganglia, along with the caudate nucleus and the putamen, the latter of which it joins to form the lentiform nucleus. Each nucleus is subdivided into internal and external parts, called globus pallidus interna and globus pallidus externa, which are separated by an internal medullary lamina.
Any line of sutures that deviates from its normal anatomical location.
A change resulting in a texture that is different from the original.
The lack of a long, narrow slit or groove that divides a tissue into distinct areas.
A congenital defect characterized by the absence of most or all of the head, with the presence of a mouth-like opening on the upper thorax.
One or more strands of fibrous amniotic tissue that can wrap around the fetus, causting constriction resulting in anatomic malformation.
A congenital heart malformation characterised by incomplete separation of the truncus arteriosus and the aorticopulmonary trunk, resulting in communication between the aorta and pulmonary trunk.

A finding of a lack of symmetry between two or more bilateral aligned primary ossific nuclei (ossification centers), typically indicated by greater stain uptake in one or more primary ossification centers as compared to others.
A congenital anatomic defect characterised by the absence of a normally present opening in an organ or tissue.
A physical quality in which the entity or structure is bowed or curved.
Of or pertaining to two lobes of an anatomic structure; divided into two lobes.

A derivative of the phthalanilide compounds. Terephthalamidine belongs to a family of compounds which appear to reversibly bind to the minor groove of the DNA double helix but not intercalate DNA. This agent also has been suggested to form ionic complexes with many biological components in vitro, including nucleic acids, proteins and lipids.
A finding of two unfused primary ossification centers, as indicated by staining, usually resulting in two separate and distinct bones.
A finding indicating that that an anatomic space or cavity is filled with blood.
A finding that the apex of the tail is rounded or dulled.
A finding referring to incomplete or absent chondrogenesis.
Joined together by cartilage.

A congenital abnormality characterized by the abnormal development of the lower portion of the body. Findings include hypoplastic lower extremities, defects of the caudal vertebrae, sacrum and neural tube, or maldeveloped gastrointestinal or genital organs.
A congenital abnormality characterized by a malformation of the head. The eyes are hypoteleric and the nose may be absent or misshapen (small, flattened, single nostril) and defective.
A developmental abnormality characterized by the complex protrusion of viscera outside the abdominal wall.
A congenital abnormality consisting of a fissure in the midline of the lip, hard and/or soft palate and upper jaw.
A congenital abnormality consisting of a fissure in the midline of the lip and upper jaw.

The grey matter adjacent to each lateral ventricle of the brain that comprises the medial dorsal striatum of the basal ganglia. The caudate nucleus is primarily involved in body and limb posture and movement.
